---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title="Philosophy | The Society" description="A distributed movement to reclaim the commons and combat digital atomization.">
  
  <article class="pt-32 pb-24 px-6 text-zinc-100 antialiased">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto space-y-12">
      
      <header class="space-y-4">
        <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-6xl font-bold tracking-tight">The Manifesto</h1>
        <p class="text-xl text-zinc-400 font-serif italic">
          “The first step in reclaiming the world is looking away from the screen.”
        </p>
      </header>

      <hr class="border-zinc-800" />

      <section class="space-y-6">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">01. The Crisis of Atomization</h2>
        <p class="text-zinc-400 leading-relaxed">
          Neoliberalism has successfully turned our social lives into a marketplace. By moving our communities onto algorithmic platforms, we have traded <strong>citizenship</strong> for <strong>usership</strong>. We are more connected than ever, yet more isolated; more “social,” yet less capable of collective action.
        </p>
        <p class="text-zinc-400 leading-relaxed">
          This is not an accident. An atomized population—one that interacts only through mediated, monetized channels—is a population that cannot organize.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-6 p-8 bg-zinc-900 rounded-2xl border border-white/5">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">02. Distributed, Not Centralized</h2>
        <p class="text-zinc-400 leading-relaxed">
          Traditional movements often fail because they are top-heavy. The Society operates on a <strong>distributed organizing model</strong>. 
        </p>
        <ul class="space-y-4">
          <li class="flex gap-4">
            <span class="text-white font-mono">A.</span>
            <span><strong class="text-zinc-200">The Local Cell:</strong> Each chapter is autonomous, making decisions based on the needs of its specific physical neighborhood.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-4">
            <span class="text-white font-mono">B.</span>
            <span><strong class="text-zinc-200">The Social Network:</strong> Our app is the “connective tissue,” allowing leaders to share resources and strategies without the noise of the public internet.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-4">
            <span class="text-white font-mono">C.</span>
            <span><strong class="text-zinc-200">The Commons:</strong> We prioritize the creation of physical spaces—parks, halls, and living rooms—that exist outside the reach of the market.</span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-6">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">03. Technology as a Tool for Exit</h2>
        <p class="text-zinc-400 leading-relaxed">
          Most apps are designed to keep you inside them. <strong>Social Network</strong> is designed to push you out. By functioning as a utilitarian bulletin board, it strips away the dopamine loops of modern social media, leaving only the logistics of rebellion.
        </p>
        <p class="text-zinc-400 leading-relaxed font-medium text-zinc-200">
          We use digital tools to build a world that eventually won’t need them.
        </p>
      </section>

      <footer class="pt-12 border-t border-zinc-800">
        <p class="text-sm text-zinc-500 mb-6">Want to learn more about the theory behind our movement?</p>
        <a href="mailto:theory@thesociety.org" class="text-white underline underline-offset-4 hover:text-zinc-300">
          Request the Reading List
        </a>
      </footer>

    </div>
  </article>

</Layout>